Introduction to the Dataset

For this project, I will be using a synthetically generated dataset titled "Global Food Wastage Dataset (2018-2024)" by Atharva Soundankar from Kaggle. This dataset includes 5000 rows of data with 8 variables that reflect data collected by world organizations such as the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) and the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).

From foodwaste.info(), the dataset is shown to contain two categorical variables and six quantitative variables. The variables and their descriptions from Kaggle are as listed:

  • Country: name of country data originated from
  • Year: year that the data was collected
  • Food Category: type of food that is wasted
  • Total Waste (Tons): total amount of food waste in tons
  • Economic Loss (Million $): estimated financial loss from food waste in millions of dollars
  • Avg Waste per Capita (Kg): average food waste generated per person in kilograms
  • Population (Million): population of country in millions
  • Household Waste (%): the percentage of food waste generated from households

From the summary of the quantitative variables in the dataset, the categorical variables Country and Food Category contain 20 and 8 unique values respectively, which means that the dataset contains food waste data from 20 different countries, where each country's data is further split into 8 different food categories. The summary also shows that the mean household waste is approximately 50% with a standard deviation of 11.60%, where the highest household waste being produced is 70% and the lowest is 30%. The household waste reaching 70% for one or more food categories and country is concerning. What is more concerning is that the highest average waste produced per person is 199.97kg compared to the lowest average waste produced per person being 20.09kg. These values show that a concerning amount and percentage of food is wasted every year for each household and person. This is reflected in the summary of Economic Loss (Million $).

Listed below are the names of each country and food category used in the dataset.

The second series of box plots contains data for the years 2018 and 2024. From the second series of box plots, the minimum total food waste for Australia has increased in 2024 compared to 2018 while the maximum total food waste remains consistent. the box plots also indicates that the interquartile range of Australia has significantly increased in 2024, showing that the amount of total waste most of the population generates has increased, which is similarly shown for Russia, the UK, Japan, Mexico, and several other countries.

Although the amount of total food waste decreases and increases each year as shown in the first series of box plots, the amount of total food waste for several countries have increased from 2018 to 2024.

sub1 = foodwaste[foodwaste["Year"] == 2018]
sub2 = foodwaste[foodwaste["Year"] == 2024]
x1 = sub1[["Total Waste (Tons)"]]
y1 = sub1[["Economic Loss (Million $)"]]
x2 = sub2[["Total Waste (Tons)"]]
y2 = sub2[["Economic Loss (Million $)"]]
In[23]:
xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = model_selection.train_test_split(x1, y1, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 111)
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression().fit(xtrain, ytrain)
ypredtrain = reg.predict(xtrain)
ypred = reg.predict(xtest)
print("Food Waste Data for 2018")
print("------------------------")
print("Training R2:", metrics.r2_score(ytrain, ypredtrain))
print("Testing R2:", metrics.r2_score(ytest, ypred), "\n")
print("Training RMSE:", np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(ytrain, ypredtrain)))
print("Testing RMSE:", np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(ytest, ypred)))

From the two linear regression machine learning models above, both use Total Waste (Tons) as the independent variable and Economic Loss (Million $) as the dependent model. The independent variable contains information about the total amount of food waste generated in the year 2018 and 2024, for each subset respectively, while the dependent variable contains information about the economic loss that this amount of waste generated for the same subsets.

There are some differences between the two models. The year 2018 model shows a high training R2 value with a slightly lowered testing R2 value, which is reflected in a RMSE value for training that is lower than for testing. This shows that the model is slightly overfitted for the year 2018 maching learning model. The year 2024 model shows a high training R2 value and a high testing R2 value, which indicates no overfitting or underfitting for the machine learning model for this specific year. This consequently leads to a RMSE value for training that is higher than for testing. Overall, the overfitting in the year 2018 model may be a result of less data points or how spread the data are from one another. The linear regression model is highly recommended for predicting variables that have a strong or mostly linear relationship.

Ethical Considerations

Since the "Global Food Wastage Dataset (2018-2024)" is a dataset that contains synthetic generations of publicly gathered and released information of a country rather than of individual persons, peoples, or groups, this dataset does not violate the ethical principles of Respect for Persons and Respect for Law and Public Interest. This dataset also does not violate the ethical principle of Beneficence since analyzing the trend of food waste within multiple countries does not pose risks to any groups as a result of the data being made to be publicly available.

Arguments against the use of this dataset can possibly be made by arguing the violation of the ethical principle of Justice due to the dataset containing information for only *20 countries* out of the 195 recognized countries in the world, but because there are *over 100 countries worldwide, the collection of food waste data of all countries may lead to a very large dataset when using the same timespan of 7 years. This makes it difficult to thoroughly analyze the vast amount of data if the data of all countries are used for this project, so this leads to minimal proof of this dataset violating the ethical principle of Justice*.

From this analysis, the generated dataset does not violate the ethical principles of Respect for Persons, Respect for Law and Public Interest, and Beneficence. Although the generated dataset may violate the ethical principle of Justice, but because of the public availability of the data of multiple countries that can be combined with this dataset, there is minimal evidence on this dataset's violation of Justice. Therefore, it can be safely concluded that this dataset does not violate any of the four ethical principles of Respect for Persons, Respect for Law and Public Interest, Beneficence, and Justice.

Conclusion

The amount of food waste has increased between 2018 and 2024 and may continue to increase. As the amount of food waste increases, the economic loss from disposing and managing the food waste rises. The tremendously large and increasing amount of money used to dispose and manage food waste is concerning because most of the money used for diposal and mangement could be used to fund other areas, such as education or research. The total amount of waste generated by different food categories show interquartile increases or decreases over seven years, with greater increases in waste generated by Bakery Items and Beverages.

A linear regression machine learning model is highly recommended to predict future trends between Total Waste (Tons) and Economic Loss (Million $) while a random forest classifier machine learning model is not recommended for this dataset, unless a binary variable is modified for this dataset. Data collection and usage of the data within this dataset is mostly ethical, but arguments could be made against the use of this dataset as it contains data for only 20 countries.

Overall, the amount of food waste increases every year in all countries, with increasing food waste in some countries becoming more concerning than others. Some machine learning models are highly recommended while other models need modifications to the dataset for effective modeling.
